    <part id="apis-and-ai-path">
      <title>APIs and AI: A Possible Path</title>
      <slide id="api-ai-evolution-1-more">
        <title>More Tools</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-1-more.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="mcp-intro">
        <title>Model Context Protocol (MCP)</title>
        <img src="mcp-logo.png" style="float: right ; width : 20% ; margin : 0% 4% 4% 4% ; "/>
        <ul>
          <li>MCP is the current <q>standard protocol</q> for LLM consumers</li>
          <li>The initial focus was on <em>additional and extended context</em></li>
          <ul>
            <li><em>Additional context</em> by providing access to the environment</li>
            <li><em>Extended context</em> by allowing MCP servers to externally manage context</li>
          </ul>
          <li>Many mapping tools generate MCP servers from OpenAPI descriptions</li>
          <li><em>What</em> to expose and <em>how to design it</em> is out of scope</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="anthropic">
        <title>Anthropic Advanced Tool Use</title>
        <img src="anthropic-advanced-tool-use.png" href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/advanced-tool-use" source='"Introducing advanced tool use on the Claude Developer Platform", November 24, 2025' class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="mcp-problems">
        <title>MCP Solves Everything!?</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Problem #1: Complex APIs will overload the MCP client's context</li>
          <li>Problem #2: Larger API landscapes will overload the MCP client's context</li>
          <li>Problem #3: Poor API design translates to poor MCP results</li>
          <li>Problem #4: Bad AX results in unsatisfactory AI results</li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="more-tools">
        <title>More Tools ⇏ Better Tool Landscape</title>
        <ul>
          <li>LLMs can now access many tools</li>
          <li>But they cannot understand many of them well</li>
          <li>Poor descriptions → poor tool selection → poor results</li>
          <li>Next: <link href="api-ai-evolution-2-description"/></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-ai-evolution-2-description">
        <title>Better Described Tools</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-2-description.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="better-descriptions">
        <title>Better Descriptions ⇏ Scalable Tool Use</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Better AX reduces confusion and misuse</li>
          <li>But even well-described tools still overload agent context</li>
          <li>The problem shifts from <em>understanding</em> tools to <em>finding</em> the right ones</li>
          <li>Next: <link href="api-ai-evolution-3-search"/></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-ai-evolution-3-search">
        <title>Dynamic Tool Discovery</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-3-search.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
      <slide id="dynamic-discovery">
        <title>Dynamic Discovery ⇏ Ideal Tool Landscape</title>
        <ul>
          <li>Discovery helps reduce tool overload</li>
          <li>Agents still have to invent workflows from scratch</li>
          <li>We need higher-level, business-aligned tools</li>
          <li>Next: <link href="api-ai-evolution-4-workflow"/></li>
        </ul>
      </slide>
      <slide id="api-ai-evolution-4-workflow">
        <title>Workflow-Based Tools</title>
        <img src="api-ai-evolution-4-workflow.png" class="fullsize-shadow" />
      </slide>
